item.title: HOW TO SHARPEN PENCILS, The People's Bailout
item.dc:creator: jtyost2
item.description:
Now OWS is launching the ROLLING JUBILEE, a program that has been in development for months. OWS is going to start buying distressed debt (medical bills, student loans, etc.) in order to forgive it. As a test run, we spent $500, which bought $14,000 of distressed debt. We then ERASED THAT DEBT. (If you’re a debt broker, once you own someone’s debt you can do whatever you want with it — traditionally, you hound debtors to their grave trying to collect. We’re playing a different game. A MORE AWESOME GAME.)
This is a simple, powerful way to help folks in need — to free them from heavy debt loads so they can focus on being productive, happy and healthy. As you can see from our test run, the return on investment approaches 30:1. That’s a crazy bargain!
Now, after many consultations with attorneys, the IRS, and our moles in the debt-brokerage world, we are ready to take the Rolling Jubilee program LIVE and NATIONWIDE, buying debt in communities that have been struggling during the recession.

item.title: How Conservative Media Lost to the MSM and Failed the Rank-and-File [Conor Friedersdorf in The Atlantic]
item.dc:creator: ouroboros
item.description:
Before rank-and-file conservatives ask, "What went wrong?", they should ask themselves a question every bit as important: "Why were we the last to realize that things were going wrong for us?"
Those audiences were misinformed.
They were operating at a self-imposed information disadvantage.
Conservatives were at a disadvantage because their information elites pander in the most cynical, self-defeating ways, treating would-be candidates like Sarah Palin and Herman Cain as if they're plausible presidents, rather than national jokes who'd lose worse than George McGovern.

item.description:
If you have a Delicious account hanging around that you haven't checked in a while, it might be worth it to swing by your user page and check that it's not displaying your REAL NAME in GIANT LETTERS right there on the page.
Mine had some initials. I have no idea how it managed that, but various people have reported that it has their real name. Now that I think about it, I think that might be what I typed in when I agreed to migrate my bookmarks.
(You can change it in the profile, don't worry.)
